                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-144" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS KINDER</persName>
                  </hi>. I received a sixpence from Barker, and gave it to Marsh the policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-145" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-145" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-145" type="surname" value="MARSH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-145" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD MARSH</persName>
                  </hi>. I assisted in taking the prisoner—I searched him</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090034"></xptr>
               <p>at the station-house, and found 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3 1/4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on him, and a good shilling—I produce two sixpences, which I received from M'Naughton and Kinder.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-146" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-146" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-146" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-146" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am inspector of coin to the Mint. Both the six-pences are counterfeit, and from the same mould.</p>
